{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3af92261-f5ae-4a9e-8c36-01b9607fa302","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Look for `.ips` crash logs here:**\n\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/          # current user crashes\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/           # system-wide crashes\n```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\n**Quick way to find the latest one:**\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them in a GUI.\n\n**Tips:**\n- The `.ips` file contains the native backtrace, signal info (e.g., `EXC_BAD_ACCESS`), and register state.\n- For NativeAOT, the frames will reference your app binary directly (not `libcoreclr`).\n- To symbolicate the crash log, you can use the `atos` tool with your app's `.dSYM` bundle (if you built with `-p:StripSymbols=false` or kept debug symbols).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f7348b39-c89e-465d-a99c-0b85bc2e2f2f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase or use tools for this.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports (`.ips` files). Let me provide the key info.","outputTokens":379,"requestId":"AC0B:359DA0:14BA58D:1720F77:6A067164"},"id":"68f7d02d-0b6e-43d2-bd53-e8b8c5aa81c8","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:05:49.770Z","parentId":"f36e621c-5aad-4b64-9b90-71f184768d5d"}
